Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <phm87> I agree that inflation have a different effect in each country : In Belgium, many things are indexed on inflation (estimated with different indexes) such as employee salaries, tax rate pivot points, social contribution pivot points and so on. The aim is then to redistribute the taxes with maximum transparency (Belgian have many data and analysis on the expenses of the govts, France is less transparent in comparison). These huge amounts of tax money are not centralized in 1 single govt but splitted to 7 entities that have their own separate budget, this system was very useful during 2008 crisis: the govts were limitated in their stupid choices.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> very interesting, and different, than the US

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <phm87> There are special rules and limits to avoid nightmares as germany faced in the 1930's: Germany didn't pay to France some war debt money so France army occupied industrial centers (Rhur) then German govt was forced to pay salaries indexed on inflation BUT as no value was created from many industries, the German Mark value plunged leading to more bank notes printed and so on

US offers try to push to buy more things to have good prices ... so it happens that they call police, navy and unrelated corps to give them army stuff (super vehicules, helicopters, ...) because they were forced to buy it. US have also the argument that they own many companies in Belgium (if Belgium buy russian stuff, US companies established in Belgium may close or move)

Content: [dscrd-hush] <phm87> BUT it is still very interesting to understand WHY so many companies unrelated to Belgium have headquarters or some buildings in Belgium : notional interests are one reason
